💥 Time is running out to apply for ELCAF 2020! 💥
~
You have until the end of tomorrow, Friday 31st January, to get those applications in... head to www.elcaf.co.uk to find  out more

Every year here at ELCAF we have a whole host of incredible guest artists and illustrators - last year the wonderful @tarabooth joined us for a talk on her life and work, discussing how she addresses vulnerability and mental health in her comics ✨
~
If you want to table alongside other incredible creators like Tara head over to www.ELCAF.co.uk, where our applications will close on January 31st

The deadline for applying to ELCAF 2020 is almost here! ✨✨✨
~
We’ll be sharing some of our favourite photos from ELCAFs past on our page over the next week and a half, so enjoy and make sure to get those applications in by January 31st on www.ELCAF.co.uk...

Tonight! 🙌 Make your way down to @owl.bookshop on Kentish Town Road for @nobrowpress’ launch party for Americana by @lukewhealy
~
Luke will be doing a talk and Q&A about his book and his approach to cartooning, with free refreshments also being provided 🍻
~
This is a free non-ticketed event, with doors opening at 6.30. See you there!
~
#Elcaf #NobrowPress #LukeHealy #Americana #BookLaunch #Illustration

If you’re feeling dazzled by the incredible and vast selection of comics, zines and other sequential works at ELCAF, festival artistic director Ligaya Salazar has created a handy guide to 10 comics everyone should read, for the folks at Stack Magazines. Every one of these works is being exhibited at this year’s event. ELCAF is open until 7pm this evening, we hope you’ll drop in!⁣
Read the article here: https://www.stackmagazines.com/art-design/10-comics-you-need-in-your-life/⁣

ELCAF is upon us! Here is your essential information for this weekend: ⁣
⁣
Where: ⁣
Round Chapel, 1d Glenarm Road, London, E5 0LY⁣
School Rooms, 2 Powerscroft Rd, E5 0PU⁣
There is no parking on site. We recommend public transport. The nearest tube line is Hackney Central, Hackney Downs and Homerton.⁣
⁣
When:⁣
7 – 9 June 2019⁣
⁣
Opening Hours:⁣
12:00 – 19:00⁣
⁣
Nearest cash points:⁣
1. Sainsburys – 13 Lower Clapton Rd, E5 0NS⁣
2. Natwest- 20 Amhurst Rd, E8 1JW⁣
3. Halifax- 402 Mare St, E8 1HN⁣
4. Santander – 392 Mare St, E8 1HP⁣
⁣
Tickets are available on the door but we recommend booking in advance via the link below.⁣
⁣
There are food, coffee and drinks stalls on site. Please bring cash with you, many of our exhibitors and food stalls will only be able to accept cash.⁣
⁣
ELCAF is suitable for families, with free entry for under 16s. ELCAF has wheelchair access, please speak to a member of staff to be taken to the wheelchair-accessible entrance. ⁣
⁣
For more information please check here: https://elcaf.co.uk/faqs/ Any other questions, don’t hesitate to get in touch. See you soon!⁣
•⁣⁣⁣⁣

Art on the Move: Take part in this considered comic making workshop on identity and migration with Brazilian artist Bárbara Malagoli (@BMalagoli) and @BlackSabaPress. Highlighting how specific the mundane can be when you are far from home, develop a story based on your memory and the places and faces of your own life. In a world of migration and movement, consider what it means to call somewhere home, and the associations attached with it no matter how far away you go.
June 9 / 5:30 pm - 7:00 pm
Suitable for ages 10+
FREE with any ELCAF ticket but come early to guarantee yourself a spot, activities will start shortly after the doors open.
•⁣

Full Programme and Tickets: www.elcaf.co.uk

Planet Plasticine! Join our pals at @BrollyLolly to create a colourful world full of plasticine figures and props. Come up with a story, create a cast of characters and creatures, and then bring it all to life in a stop-motion animated video.
You’ll need a mobile phone, the Stop Motion Studio app (download this for free before the workshop), and your imagination!
June 9 / 3:45 pm - 5:15 pm
FREE with any ELCAF TICKET but come early to guarantee yourself a spot, activities will start shortly after the doors open.

Printed Pennants: Illustrator and ELCAF 2018 Award winner @AkvileMagicdust invites you into the secret world of flags. Create colourful banners (pennants) of textiles using linocut techniques. Using a bit of designing, sewing and printing, voilà! – you’ll have your own personal banner to take home with you!
June 9 / 2:00 pm - 3:30 pm
Suitable for ages 10+

Use postcards, tickets, photographs and other images as a starting point to illustrate and bring the game to life.

On Sunday at ELCAF, our 2019 artist-in-residence, Jon McNaught (@jonmcn), will talk about the process of creating his critically acclaimed comic book, Kingdom, which explores the landscapes of a caravan site on the British coast and the beauty and boredom of childhood holidays.
Jon will take us through initial ideas and research, to final artwork. He will also talk about printmaking, poetry, and the use of comics to explore distant memories and the passing of time.
June 9 / 4:45 pm - 5:45 pm
FREE with ELCAF ALL ACCESS TICKET
Please note all talks have limited seat capacity and will be available on a first come first served basis. We cannot guarantee a place with your ticket so please be there early to secure a seat, talks will begin shortly after the doors open.

Comics/identity: How can comics fill the gap between contemporary art and popular culture? How can it be something both futile and committed? A link between a home country and a foster one? Join illustrator @MelekZertal as she talks about her work and considers these questions, as well as pondering why she keeps drawing sad lesbian love stories.

Self-help and Surfing: Hear illustrator and author AJ Dungo (@agedungs) discuss his beautiful new graphic novel, In Waves, which deals with love, loss, and the solace of surfing. Take a peek into the process of how the book came together, the role of comics in escapism, and about all of the relationships that paved the way for his first collaboration with @NobrowPress.

Launched at ELCAF back in 2015, Small Press publisher Joe Pearson has run @DesignForToday for four years. After a warehouse fire in which most of his stock was lost, Joe is now re-launching with a clutch of new books from Emma Lewis, Alice Pattullo, Clive Hicks-Jenkins and Alex Barrow – and is more determined than ever to carry on. In this talk Joe discusses his publishing, why he started, how he collaborates, and the challenges of small publishing in a world dominated by multinational publishers and discount sellers.

Join author, illustrator and art director @rui.tenreiro as he chats about comic artists from Southern and Eastern Africa with Sam Arthur from @Nobrowpress. Focuses will include the post-revolution, government sponsored comics from 1980’s Mozambique, Mozambican comics today (including Rui’s own work), Tanzanian comics from Dar es Salaam, and the South African comics of Mogorosi Motshumi and the Capetonian collective K.I.F.
